   "source": [
    "# Part 1: Reading & Reflection (20 points)\n",
    "\n",
    "### Required Reading\n",
    "[Multimodal Few-Shot Learning with Frozen Language Models](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2106.13884)\n",
    "\n",
    "[Quality Not Quantity: On the Interaction between Datase Design and Robustness of CLIP\n",
    "](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2208.05516.pdf)\n",
    "\n",
    "[Generative AI: Here to stay, but for good?](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0160791X2300177X)\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### Questions\n",
    "1. What types of multimodal data noise are typically present in multimodal datasets, and how can they negatively impact the performance of a model during training? Can you provide examples of multimodal data points that might be considered noisy? Furthermore, how might we develop estimators capable of distinguishing between noisy and noise-free multimodal data pairs? If you have unlimited fundings to use for data filtering and data cleaning, what would be the ideal way to clean the multimodal dataset?\n",
    "\n",
    "2. What is the intuition of utilizing frozen large language models as the backbone for multimodal tasks? Which types of encoders would facilitate the integration of diverse information into a format understandable by LLMs? How do these LLMs process and interpret information from different modalities?\n",
    "\n",
    "3. Ensuring the effectiveness of multimodal foundation models through high-quality instruction tuning is vital. A study detailed at [here](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2402.04333.pdf) introduces a strategy for selecting significant data specifically suited for enhancing instruction tuning for language models. A primary challenge in this approach is determining which data are most crucial for targeted instruction tuning. How can we accurately identify and select the most impactful data for enhancing instruction tuning in multimodal foundation models? Given the complexity of diverse and multimodal information, what strategies can ensure the effectiveness of instruction tuning data for specific tasks?\n",
    "\n",
    "4. With the advancement of generative AI, distinguishing between AI-generated and human-created content is becoming increasingly challenging. Besides watermarking, which has its limitations, are there other effective methods to differentiate between AI-generated and human-created content across various modalities (text, audio, video, image)? Or is it becoming virtually impossible to make this distinction?\n",
    "\n",
    "5. For state-of-the-art video generation models like Sora, Yann Lecun mentioned in [here](https://twitter.com/ylecun/status/1758740106955952191) that Sora does not understand the real world and its corresponding physical rules. Do you agree with this view? Can the future development of generative AI systems truly incorporate real-world knowledge, or are they limited in this aspect? Is pursuing generative AI a viable path towards achieving Artificial General Intelligence (AGI)?\n",
    "\n",
    "### Response\n",
    "1. Multimodal datasets often contain several types of noise, including semantic mismatches between modalities and modality-specific corruption. For example, some noise that can appear in multimodal datasets are images that are captioned incorrectly or distorted audio, messy notes, etc. Though intuitively one might think training on more data is always better, but incorporating these noisy data, the signal for the model to learn from is less clear, which can negatively impact the performance of the model. The \"Quality Not Quantity\" paper proposes CLIP-based filtering for image-text pairs. By scoring each pair based on their CLIP similarity and removing those pairs with low scores, the dataset now has reduced noise. If unlimited resources were available, an ideal pipeline would combine automated filtering use pretrained multimodal models and large-scale human verification and possibly include active learning to iteratively identify and correct noisy examples.\n",
    "2. The intuition behind utilizing frozen multimodal LLMs as the backbone for multimodal tasks is that LLMs already contain extensive linguistic knowledge and reasoning ability to learn from a large-scale text corpus. Instead of retraining these models from scratch, multimodal systems and use modality-specific encoders such as vision encoders (e.g. Resnet) and text encoders (such as BERT) that transform non-text inputs into embeddings compatible with the LLM's token space. Projection layers or adapters are then used to convert these embeddings into sequences of tokens that the transformer can process. The LLM is frozen, and the system only needs to learn the smaller bridging components.\n",
    "3. To accurately identify and select the best data for enhacing instruction tuning in multimodal foundation models, we need to first identify samples that provide the more informative signal for the target tasks. One way to do this is data filtering using model-based scoring, such as constrastive loss score or ensemble gain. Nguyen et al. mention that ensemble gain (when performance improves when combining predictions from multiple models) often correlate with poor robustness to distribution shifts, and this could indicate poor dataset quality. Additionally, we want to maximize diversity across and within modalities by selecting points that represent the entire dataset.\n",
    "The paper uses gradient similarity to choose training datapoints. This is efficient because most of the computation is done once, with the gradient features being computed for training and then re-computed with few-shot validation examples for each task. \n",
    "4. Distinguishing between AI and human-generated content is becoming increasingly difficult as generative models improve. Within text, many have noticed small grammatical commonalities in AI-generated text, such as the overuse of em-dashes or semicolons or excessive use of phrases such as \"leverage\", \"delve into\", and any formal transition word. However, this is easily combatted by a simple user prompt to avoid this \"AI-isms\". Many online AI Detectors exist as well, often used by teachers in school, with some models achieving accuracies of 95% ([Durak et. al](https://doi.org/10.1111/ejed.70014)). More sophisticated techniques include forensic detection that spot anomalies in frequency of images or patterns in text and content provenance that records the origin and modification history of digital content.\n",
    "5. Though I do not have a strong and fully formed opinion, I agree with Yann Lecun that generative models do not yet understand the real world. Gen AI as it is right now functions by predicting patterns in data, not by experiencing or comprehending the physical world. Future AI systems could incorporate real-world knowledge by integrating world models, robotics, and simulation to test predictions and learn causal relationships. However, purely generative models are probably unlikely to reach a high level of understanding of the world. For this reason, pursuing gen AI alone is not a viable path towards achiving AGI."
   ]
  },
