    "## Questions to Answer:\n",
    "\n",
    "*   Explain some possible issues with converting non-image data into images (even if you did not have to do so, discuss what could be some issues).\n",
    "\n",
    "*   What are some possible issues with using visual representations of your data. Discuss some drawbacks of doing this (if you did not have to do the conversion as your data was already in the form of images, then discuss the drawbacks of converting those images to another modality like text, audio, etc.).\n",
    "\n",
    "* Discuss the strategy you decided on how to split your data into train/test splits. Why did you settle on this? Were any other alternative splits considered?\n",
    "\n",
    "## Response\n",
    "1. An issue with converting non-image data into images is that you lose some domain knowledge. In its original modality, audio or music contain more data-rich information that spectrograms or wave plots cannot necessarily capture. Another issue that can arise is missingness or sparsity. If many values are missing or zero, the resulting image can carry little signal. Lastly, you can lose interpretability.\n",
    "2. An issue with converting images to another modality such as text is information loss. A few words or sentences describing in image is far from enough in fully capturing the image. You may lose information about the spatial structure of the image and highlight certain objects while ignoring others.\n",
    "3. I used the pre-defined train/test splits provided by the derek-thomas/ScienceQA dataset, which were curated by the original authors to ensure a balanced distribution across subjects, grade levels, and question types. This is preferable to a random split because it avoids data leakage from related questions (e.g., questions drawn from the same lecture) appearing in both splits. An alternative would have been a stratified random split by subject or grade, but the canonical splits are well-established in the literature and ensure reproducibility.\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
